{
    "_id" : ObjectId("603690eb0c817f0398fabec5"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/How-do-I-find-a-product-manager-job-in-Tokyo?-",
    "answer" : "This answer comes in two parts. First, the availability of product management jobs in Japan has been low. I have kept an eye on the job market for the past 8 years and until recently, product management jobs were rare. This corresponds to a general observation that product management is not a well-defined profession in Japan (and in other countries), and foreign firms operating in Japan would typically have product management based in the HQ. Recently however, there have been more foreign companies posting product management jobs in Japan, perhaps because LinkedIn is becoming more widely used in Japan. This is a welcome development and one that I am examining for myself.  My sense so far is that most of these recent jobs are regional product management, not core product management. That means the regional PM gives input to the PM at HQ. And depending on the company, there may or may not be much that results from that. Of course, the case of a company having development based in the region is an exception, and I haven't run across that yet. The second part of this answer is about language ability and native bias. Almost all foreign firms posting jobs in Japan make high-level Japanese proficiency a requirement. However, a foreigner with the necessary skills may not have that proficiency. So what often happens is the company keeps trying to find bilingual candidates who can possibly step up to the job. Often the foreign company will default to a native Japanese candidate who may have some of the skills and whose English is passable. Sadly, this often does not work because language ability is really the tip of the iceberg. For example, a native Japanese person will be more reticent and not so aggressive in terms of communicating with the foreign HQ. Most tech companies in the US require a high degree of pushiness to achieve a minimal level of communication. And if the person does not really understand the nature of the role, he/she will be more isolated in general and may never get the picture. So in conclusion, my sense is that foreign companies are starting on the path to having regional product management in Japan, but there will be a learning period as they figure out what works and doesn't work. And even if they find the perfect candidate, that person may not have as much control as would normally be the case, back in HQ.",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-24T17:46:19.683Z"),
    "question" : "How do I find a product manager job in Tokyo? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

