    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/What-things-are-common-between-a-product-management-and-a-technology-consulting-job?-",
    "answer" : "(Since I consult to technology companies around product management...) In both cases, it's critical to first understand the client's actual (and perceived) problems including relative priority/urgency.  What's not working, underlying root causes, organizational or architectural issues.  I'm always trying to do situation analysis and confirm that with clients BEFORE proposing solutions and starting work.  That exactly mirrors the product management prime directive to deeply understand markets/segments/customers/users/needs BEFORE spec'ing and building some expensive widget. Then, it's critical to find some quick/early wins in the consulting process.  What success or improvement can we demonstrate in days/weeks?  (Unless you're a Big 4 firm with a F500 client who has $100M's to spend as quickly as possible.)  Shared success and joint confidence-building are critical to healthy consulting relationships.  Resequencing of project elements is to be expected.  Frequent status reports and interim deliverables matter.That closely aligns with prodmgmt's roadmapping challenge.  How to get a a few important things done soon, rather than many partially statred but never finished?  How to demonstrate to customers/stakeholders that you can ship incremental value often and still get the really big things done?",
